{{Sky|06|47|50.5|+|70|14|55}} {{Infobox galaxy cluster | name = | image = [[Image:MACS0647-JD.jpg|300px]] | caption = MACS J0647.7+7015 | credit = Hubble Space Telescope | epoch = 2000 | constellation = [[Camelopardalis]] | ra = {{RA|06|47|42}} | dec = {{DEC|+70|15}} | brightest_member = | member_no = | richness = | bmtype = | velocity_dispersion = | redshift = 0.592<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ebeling|first=Harald|author2=Elizabeth Barrett |author3=David Donovan |author4=Cheng-Jiun Ma |author5=Alastair Edge |author6=Leon van Speybroeck |title=A Complete Sample of 12 Very X-Ray Luminous Galaxy Clusters at z > 0.5|journal=Astrophysical Journal Letters|date=2007|volume=661|page=33|doi=10.1086/518603|bibcode = 2007ApJ...661L..33E |arxiv = astro-ph/0703394 }}</ref> | distance = {{convert|2180|Mpc|Mly|0|abbr=on|lk=on}} {{hub|0.70}} | temperature = 13.3 ± 1.80 [[Electron volt|keV]] | mass = 2.07 ± 0.10{{e|14}} {{hub|0.70}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Zitrin|first=Adi|author2=Tom Broadhurst |author3=Rennan Barkana |author4=Yoel Rephaeli |author5=Narciso Benítez |title=Strong-lensing analysis of a complete sample of 12 MACS clusters at z > 0.5: mass models and Einstein radii|journal=MNRAS|date=2011|issue=410|page=1939|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2966.2010.17574.x|url=http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/bib_query?2011MNRAS.410.1939Z|accessdate=5 August 2013|arxiv = 1002.0521 |bibcode = 2011MNRAS.410.1939Z }}</ref> | luminosity = 32.5 ± 2.1 {{e|44}} [[erg]] s<sup>−1</sup> (bolometric) | flux = | other_names = }}
'''MACS J0647.7+7015''' is a [[galaxy cluster]] with a [[redshift]] ''z'' = 0.592, located at [[J2000.0]] [[right ascension]] {{RA|06|47|42}} [[declination]] {{DEC|+70|15}}. It lies between the [[Big Dipper]] and [[Little Dipper]] in the constellation [[Camelopardalis]]. It is part of a sample<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ebeling|first=Harald|author2=Elizabeth Barrett |author3=David Donovan |author4=Cheng-Jiun Ma |author5=Alastair Edge |author6=Leon van Speybroeck |title=A Complete Sample of 12 Very X-Ray Luminous Galaxy Clusters at z > 0.5|journal=Astrophysical Journal Letters|date=2007|volume=661|page=33|doi=10.1086/518603|accessdate=|bibcode = 2007ApJ...661L..33E |arxiv = astro-ph/0703394 }}</ref> of 12 extreme galaxy clusters at ''z'' > 0.5 discovered by the [[MAssive Cluster Survey (MACS)]].
During 2012 the galaxy cluster was announced as [[gravitational lens|gravitationally lensing]] the most distant [[galaxy]] ([[MACS0647-JD]]), then ever imaged (''z'' = 11).<ref>{{Cite journal |author= Dan Coe |title= CLASH: Three Strongly Lensed Images of a Candidate z ~ 11 Galaxy |arxiv= 1211.3663 |date= November 15, 2012 |display-authors=etal |doi=10.1088/0004-637X/762/1/32 |volume=762 |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |page=32 |bibcode=2013ApJ...762...32C}}<!--|accessdate= November 18, 2012 --></ref><ref>Youtube, [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m2IV4-UkbGQ Zoom on galaxy cluster MACS J0647.7+7015]</ref><ref>[http://content.ebscohost.com/pdf27_28/pdf/2011/81Z/21Jan11/71689120.pdf?T=P&P=AN&K=71689120&S=R&D=aph&EbscoContent=dGJyMMvl7ESeqLM4yOvsOLCmr0qep7NSsa24SLCWxWXS&ContentCustomer=dGJyMPGssk2xqLJNuePfgeyx44Hy Strong-lensing analysis of a complete sample of 12 MACS clusters at z > 0.5: mass models and Einstein radii]{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>NASA Hubblesite, [http://hubblesite.org/newscenter/archive/releases/2012/36/image/b/ NASA Great Observatories Find Candidate for Most Distant Galaxy Yet Known]</ref>
