{{Infobox book | name = The Birth Order Book | image = The birth order book.jpg | caption = Hardcover edition, 1980s | author = [[Kevin Leman]] | title_orig = <!-- if not in English --> | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = English | series = | subject = [[Birth order]] | genre = | published = 1982, 1998(revised) | media_type = Print, e-book, audiobook | pages = 352 pages | isbn = 1606710710 | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = | wikisource = }} '''''The Birth Order Book: Why You Are the Way You Are''''' is a 1982 non-fiction book by [[Kevin Leman|Dr. Kevin Leman]] on [[birth order]] and its potential influence on personality and development.<ref>{{cite news|title=BIRTH ORDER: IS THE OLDEST THE WISEST?|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=PI&s_site=philly&p_multi=PI&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB29971CBDD7DD4&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=22 September 2013|newspaper=Philadelphia Inquirer|date=May 12, 1985}}</ref> An updated and revised version of the book was published in 1998 through [[Baker Publishing Group]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Pecking order|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AT&p_theme=at&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EADA418AD996AAB&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=22 September 2013|newspaper=Atlanta Journal|date=December 25, 1998}}</ref> Leman first began studying birth orders while a student at the [[University of Arizona]] and noticing that several elements of personality were associated with a person's birth order rank.<ref>{{cite news|last=Harrigan|first=Stephen|title=Places, Everyone|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=wVZTAAAAIBAJ&sjid=54QDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6916,5428866&dq=birth-order-book+leman&hl=en|accessdate=22 September 2013|newspaper=Deseret News|date=Apr 28, 1993}}</ref>
==Synopsis== In the book Leman details four types of personality based upon the individual's birth order: First Born, Only Child, Middle Child, and Last Born.<ref>{{cite news|last=Towarnicky|first=Carol|title=Birth Order: Determine Your Destiny|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=milmAAAAIBAJ&sjid=U4gNAAAAIBAJ&pg=1177,1993278&dq=birth-order-book+leman&hl=en|accessdate=22 September 2013|newspaper=Edmonton Journal|date=Jun 16, 1985}}</ref> Only Child types are considered to be a form of the First Born personality types, but "in triplicate".<ref name="CBS">{{cite web|last=Neal|first=Rome|title=Personality Traits Linked To Birth Order|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/2100-500172_162-511694.html|publisher=CBS News|accessdate=22 September 2013}}</ref>
*'''First Born''': First born children are described as leaders that are often perfectionists that desire approval from those in charge. Leman also states that first borns are "typically aggressive" but are also often people pleasers.<ref name="CBS" /> *'''Middle Child''': Middle children are sometimes diverse in that they are "guaranteed to be opposite of their older sibling" and often have the feeling that they are ignored in favor of their older and younger siblings. They are also described as having personalities that lean towards being secretive and can often serve as peacemakers between their older and younger siblings.<ref name="CBS" /> *'''Last Born''': Leman describes the last children as "social and outgoing" but also the "most financially irresponsible of all birth orders". He also comments that they have the potential to be manipulative as well as charming.<ref name="CBS" />
==Reception== Reception for ''The Birth Order Book'' and the theories espoused in the book has been mixed,<ref>{{cite news|title=No kidding: Birth order may not count|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=ET&p_theme=et&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=1155B5249F37AB30&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=22 September 2013|newspaper=Erie Times-News|date=November 12, 2006}}</ref> with some commenting that there are "many variables" that have an effect on the personality aside from birth order.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gray|first=Dawn|title=Pecking Order|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1996-07-14/features/9607140069_1_birth-order-birth-order-book-secondborn|accessdate=22 September 2013|date=July 14, 1996}}</ref> In a 1995 article in the [[Los Angeles Times]], [[University of Texas]] professor Toni Falbo commented that the modern family dynamic is "quite complex" and that "[relying] too heavily on birth order for answers is a mistake" due to families being "much more complicated now" due to the addition of step-siblings, half-siblings, and other various factors.<ref>{{cite news|last=Howard|first=Rebecca|title='90s FAMILY : How Birth Order Stamps Personality|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-02-15/news/ls-32289_1_birth-order|accessdate=22 September 2013|newspaper=LA Times|date=February 15, 1995}}</ref>
